  "opinion": "As a hairdresser in Chicago, I spend a lot of time on social media every day, chatting with clients and friends, sharing my creative hairstyles, and keeping up with trends. Fake content is a real headache—it’s everywhere, from wild conspiracy theories to photoshopped images that make people feel bad about themselves. I’ve seen it firsthand in my community, especially among immigrants like me who might trust sources that aren’t reliable. My approach is pretty straightforward: I don’t take things at face value. If I see a shocking post, I pause and check it out before sharing. I use simple tools like reverse image searches or just asking around in my network—other hairdressers, family, or church friends—to see if it’s legit. Being creative helps me spot fakes because I notice when things look off, like weird lighting in a photo or inconsistent stories. I’m not super organized, so I don’t have a strict system, but I make it a habit to question everything. Social media platforms should do more, too—they need to flag fake stuff clearly and make it easier for regular folks like us to report it without a hassle. At the end of the day, it’s about protecting our minds and relationships. I talk to my kids about this, teaching them to be skeptical and kind online, just like in real life. It’s a constant battle, but staying alert and connected with people I trust makes it manageable.",
